            <div class="section plan-info first-bg">
                <h2 class="subtitle">Source of the Problem</h2>
                <br>
                <p>We may all believe that what we eat has minimal impact on the environment and that other larger factors are far more harmful. However, many app users are surprised to learn that food and the lifestyle choices we make everyday account for more than 24% of climate problems. Each individual feels helpless when it comes to climate change, although the fact that you are reading our website is a start! Your personal choices can have a big impact on climate change!</p>
                <p>In fact, studies show that even just eating steak contains 330g CO2 which is like driving a car for 3 miles. Instead, a huge bowl of lentils is like 2 grams of Co2! Here is how you can improve your eating habits and save the environment.</p>
                <p>The worst example is cows' meat, cows produce 25 times more potent than CO2. It takes so many resources to provide cows with a healthy life such as land, fertiliser, water and about 1 billion tons of grain. If this grain was invested to feed humans greenhouse emissions would fall.</p>
                <p>The vegetarian and vegan diets have the least impact on the environment, although it’s not much different in terms of greenhouse emissions. Humans are eating around twice as much meat as their healthy diet requires. We are not saying to cut out meat but to reduce it, focusing on legumes, green food, white meats and fish for nutrients. For example following a Mediterranean Diet will help reduce climate change by 15%.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="section plan-info second-bg">
                <h2 class="subtitle">Overconsumption</h2>
                <br>
                <p>Food waste is a significant issue, with one-third or more of food being thrown away, primarily at the household level. This wastage not only costs money but also harms the environment by wasting water, oil, and other natural resources that went into producing it.</p>
                <p>There are many effective ways to reduce food waste and for a start when you enter our website there is a section devoted to finding the right amount of calories that is right for you. Remember we do not imply that you need to count calories, but we want to make sure you understand the right amount of food that is right to nourish, energize and feed your body.  Some ways to eat the right amount of food for your body are:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Familiarise yourself with your portion sizes</li>
                    <li>Include food rich in fibre, protein, complex carbohydrates</li>
                    <li>Understand your hunger queues and don’t mistake them for thirst!</li>
                    <li>Drink a lot of water</li>
                    <li>Slow down when you eat</li>
                    <li>If you finish eating, and you are still hungry, wait 15 minutes before eating again.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>By implementing these strategies, households can significantly reduce the amount of food they waste. Planning meals and proper food storage to prevent overbuying, overeating and early spoilage can really make a difference. </p>
                <img style="width: 80vw" src="../images_and_videos/Overconsumption.png">
