            <div class="section plan-info first-bg">
                <h2 class="subtitle">Carbohydrates</h2>
                <p>Carbohydrates are sugar molecules and the main nutrients in our diets. Carbs reserve energy for the body and supply carbon atoms for other syntheses. When choosing more environmentally friendly carbohydrates, it’s important to consult the label of the grains, legumes, lentil pasta, bananas, and apples that you are buying. Here is a list of things you should look out for when buying carbohydrates:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Look at the Nutrition Facts labels to find choices lower in sodium, saturated (solid) fat, and sugars. All damaging ingredients for the environment.</li>
                    <li>When choosing fruits and vegetables, which fall under the carb category choose kilometre 0 produce.</li>
                    <li>Look for the word “whole” at the beginning of the ingredients list</li>
                    <li>Foods that say “multi-grain,” “100% wheat,” “high fibre,” or are brown may not be whole grain products. </li>
                    <li>Buy whole-grain products that are tightly packaged and well-sealed. Grains should always look and smell fresh. Also, check the expiration date and storage guidelines on the package.</li>
                    <li>Purchase smaller quantities of whole grain products to reduce spoilage. Most grains in sealed packaging can be kept in the freezer.</li>
                    <li>Reduce the shelf life of grains. Most whole grain flours keep well in the refrigerator for 2 to 3 months and in the freezer for 6 to 8 months. </li>
                </ul>
                <img style="width: 25vw" src="../images_and_videos/Carbs.png">
            </div>

            <div class="section plan-info second-bg">
                <h2 class="subtitle">Healthy Fats</h2>
                <p>A healthy diet should always include healthy fats. There are two types of healthy fats that need to be included for a healthy diet: monounsaturated and polyunsaturated fats. Monounsaturated fats have a double bond between 2 carbon atoms while polyunsaturated fats have more than three double bonds between 2 carbon atoms. These fats provide your body with omega 3 and omega 6, which are things it's important that we incorporate them into our diets. </p>
                <p>Plant-based choices like avocados, nuts, flax, tofu, edamame, chia seeds or olive oil are great alternative sources for this type of fat. However, it's important to understand that not all types of oils have the same benefits. Trans fatty acids or saturated fatty acids are commonly found in commercial foods like crackers, cookies or fast food and should be avoided in favour of healthy unsaturated options. </p>
                <p>Monounsaturated and polyunsaturated fats are considered "heart healthy fats". They help lower cholesterol, reduce the risk of heart diseases and stroke.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="section plan-info first-bg">
                <h2 class="subtitle">The transition</h2>
                <p>The transition to a sustainable diet can be quite tricky, the first step to make is to implement more plant-based foods and to follow the guidelines we spoke about above. This change will also have a big impact on both your health and the environment. Luckily the consumption of plant-based foods has risen and if we all increased this it would make a huge difference. To make sustainable choices in our daily lives, concentrate on reducing overconsumption, focus on plant-based proteins, eating more vegetables and fruits, eating complex carbs and healthy fats, eating local foods… You will be able to succeed in creating a healthier lifestyle and environment! Don't get discouraged because we can grow as a community, look at the graph below we are slowly growing but if we get your help we can reach our goal.</p>
